>Chapter 4: Be Together
>Fall winds blow as you trudge up the mountain
>Raquel and you were backpack hiking
>You had taken time off work for this
>A week long trek, going up the California mountains, through the redwood forests, maybe even a bit of abalone diving
>Backpacking wasn’t something you had done before, Raquel talked you into it
>Usually a few hour hike sated your need for the outdoors
>Raquel as besides you as you walked through the trees up the mountain
>"These aren’t mountains ya know, these are big hills" she says as she fidgets with one of her rucksack straps
>"Bullshit these are mountains, that’s what we called them on the east coast" you retort quickly
>You reach over and help her with the strap
>"That’s because they never saw REAL mountains, ones with snow caps!" she says as she slaps away your hand playfully
>"HEY I’ve climbed mount Fuji! Don’t mess with me!"
>You pull a kung Fu stance
>She’s laughs loudly
>God you love that laugh
>"What’s Japan like anyway?" she asks through a laugh
>The sun is slowly descending, the sky burns orange and red 
>The only traces of civilization are contrail etches across the skies
>You think for a moment
>"It’s...different... in a good way" you say as you stop and look around
>"Let’s set up camp over there" 
>You point to a small clearing next to a downed redwood
>"What do you mean different?" Raquel asks, dropping her pack roughly and leaning it against a stump
>"I mean I didn’t fit in there at all, the people were nice and friendly and the food was good but..."
>You stare off into the distance
>"But?" she asks sliding up to you 
>"The showers are too short for starters, people always want pictures because you’re different and have to sense of personal space" you say as you pull the 2 person tent out of your pack
>"I enjoyed the sights and such but god they are such a collective community that they seem almost 2 faced" 
>You had taken a few culture classes on your days
>Japan had a very collective culture, America and most of Europe were individual focused
>You start setting up the tent and swear gently as you struggle against it
>Raquel grabs a few of the stakes and pushes them in so they are upright, waiting for you to hammer them in
>You glance over at her occasionally
>She’s a total doll and you can’t help but feel lucky to have her here with you
>Her dark fur contrasts her bright yellow shirt with the words "Make music not war" printed in pink letters 
>Her stump has a small red ribbon wrapped around it
